📊 Healthy Kids Nutrition & Growth Analysis
README Document
📌 Project Overview

This project focuses on analyzing children's health data to understand the relationship between nutrition, lifestyle habits, and physical growth. The analysis is performed using Microsoft Excel, leveraging data cleaning, calculations, pivot tables, and dashboard creation techniques.

The goal is to identify patterns in BMI, dietary habits, screen time, and regional differences to support better health decisions.

🎯 Objectives

Calculate Body Mass Index (BMI) for each child

Categorize children into health groups (Underweight, Healthy, Overweight, Obese)

Analyze the impact of:

Fruit & vegetable intake

Sugar consumption

Screen time

Compare health trends across different regions and age groups

Build an interactive dashboard for visualization

📂 Dataset Description

The dataset (Child_Health_Data.csv) contains the following fields:

Child ID

Age (in months)

Gender

Height (cm)

Weight (kg)

Daily fruit servings

Daily vegetable servings

Daily sugar drink intake

Screen time (hours)

Region

🛠 Tools & Technologies

Microsoft Excel – Data cleaning and analysis

Pivot Tables – Data summarization

Charts – Visualization

Slicers – Dashboard interactivity

🔄 Step-by-Step Workflow
1️⃣ Data Cleaning

Converted raw data into an Excel table

Checked for missing and duplicate values

Ensured consistent formatting

2️⃣ Feature Engineering

Created BMI column using formula:

BMI = Weight (kg) / (Height (m))²

Created Health_Status column:

Underweight

Healthy Weight

Overweight

Obese

3️⃣ Data Analysis
📊 Health Status by Age

Used Pivot Tables to analyze BMI categories across age groups

🍎 Nutrition vs BMI

Compared fruit & vegetable intake with average BMI

📱 Lifestyle Impact

Studied relationship between:

Sugar consumption

Screen time

Health status

🌍 Regional Analysis

Compared BMI and nutrition patterns across regions

4️⃣ Dashboard Creation

Built an interactive dashboard including:

Bar charts

Scatter plots

Pivot charts

Added slicers for:

Gender

Region

Health status

📈 Key Insights

Higher fruit and vegetable intake is linked to healthier BMI levels

Increased sugar consumption correlates with overweight and obesity

More screen time is associated with poor health outcomes

Certain regions show lower nutrition intake and higher BMI trends

💡 Recommendations

Encourage healthy eating habits through school nutrition programs

Reduce sugary drink consumption among children

Promote physical activity to reduce screen time

Focus on regions with poor nutrition awareness

